{"/service/ndnp/kyu/batch_kyu_judaspriest_ver01/data/sn86069657/00280763561/1914010101/0007.xml":{"full_text":"THE TIMES.\nrUBMSUKl KVEKT THOKSDAT.\nSubscription rates $1 a year or three\nyears in tulvnce 82.\n.1- 12. lSurghcr, l'ubllshcr.\nEntered as second-class mail matter.\nThursday, January 1, 1914.\nCLUB RATES.\nFor the convenience of our sub\nscribers, we have arranged club rates\nwith the following papers at prices\nbelow mentioned:\nThe Times and\nCourier-Journal tl.00\nCincinnati Enquirer 1.10\nLouisville Herald 90\nHome and Farm 75\nInland Farmer .75\nAmerican Farmer 90\nSouthern Agriculturist 75\nOur Stanton correspondent\njuetlv pays a nice compliment to\nkis town in speaking of it as a\nbeautiful place in which to live,\nft is always pleasanter to mention\nthe good things we see and have\nthan to speak of the bad. Still,\nit sometimes becomes our pain\nful duty to mention very unpleas\nantly some of the things we are\nforced to observe and know, ev\non against our will. It would be\nt(nod if we could only see roses\nand smiles in our pathway of life,\nbut such conditions do not exist.\nThus in our humble efforts to\ni-.orrecr some of the distasteful\nthings we learn of, wo are forced\nbo refer to them, when in our\nkearts we would rather not, but\ndeal only with the pleasant things\nOf life. We are sure, however,\nthat we, in common with all men,\ndo deal too extensively with the\ndark side of life's travels. We\nkope that we will be able to keep\ndown one new leaf in our New\nYear resolutions: \"Deal more\ngently, yet positively, with our\nenemies.\" Not our personal en\ndmies, for we are living in the\nkope that of such we have none,\nbut tile enemies of our govern\nment, our society, and our religion.\nThe Legislators of the coming\nGeneral Assembly in mapping\nout. plans of proceedings, have\nnever, to our knowledge, includ\ned a bill to cut railroad passan\nijf r rates from 3 cents to 2 cents\nper mile. What a saving this\nwould be to our people if we hud\nuch a law. The Times is the\ndnly paper in the State agitating\ntwo-cent mile rate. This is\nwhy the peeplo are not clamor\ning for it. This has no effect on\nthe Times, we are for the right\nthing, though we stand alone.\nMany other States have a two\ncent rate, why not Kentucky?\nWhen the Legislature convenes\nand fails to pass such a law they\nare equal (to allowing the rail\nroads of the Stato to confiscate\n50 cents of the traveler's hard\nearned cash every time they earn\n$1 justly. This is too biga swin\ndle for our State Legislature to\nparticipate in by an omission of\na sacred duty to Kentucky citi\nr.ons. If the people of the State\nwould send a petition to their\nrepresentatives asking them to\nhelp pass such a law, it might\ndo some good.\nIt was probably the happiest\nmoment of President Wilson's\nlife us President of the United\nState?, when he signed the new\ncurrency law on Dec. !Mrd. It is\nneedless to m.v that thi bill is\nthe greatest masterpiece of states.\nmanship enacted within the last\nforty years. Under the wise pro\nvisions of this bill there will nev\ner be another financial panic such\nas wo had under Iloopevolt in\n1007 and under Cleveland (which\nho inherited from Pres. Harri\nson) in 1803. In other words\nthis bill will make money easy\nand plentiful everywhere. When\naver a banker has loaned all the\nmonoy to tho business'mon of\nts community that itjean Jsparo,\nand still has culls for more loans,\ntho bank can take the stocks,\nbonds and mortgages and other\nfirst-class securities and turn\nthem over to tho Government, re\ngional bank and get more money\nwith which to accommodate its\nborrowers. It is this element in\nthe bill which will render our\ncurrency elastic so that it will\nexpand automatically in accord\nance with the requirements of\nbusiness in every state and coun\nty of the United States.\ni!roiffli!iiiiniMimmim\ni\nFOR $1.25 WE WILL SEND YOU\nTHE CLAY CITY TIMES,\nTHE OHIO FARMER, -TODAYS\nMAGAZINE, -McCALL'S\nMAGAZINE,\n(Weekly) ONE YEAR\n(Weekly) ONE YEAR\n(Monthly) ONE YEAR\n(Monthly) ONE YEAR\nONE MAE\nONE Mc\nCAB.\nRanton pattern\nPATTERN\nPatterns to he selected from First Numbers of\nToday's and ScCalTs Received.\nTJndoimtedly the Season s (greatest Subscription Bargain\n3\nB\n3\nSB\n3\ns\nLet us take courage when we\nthink of the probability of a law\nbeing passed by the incoming\nLegislature which will give us\nState Aid for roads. A feature\nshould be incorporated in the bill\nto the effect that the citizens ot\nany county, if such county fails\nto take advantage of the State\nAid, may form a club und by\nputting up a sum of money or\nguaranteed labor, mav secure\nfrom the State a sum equal to.\nwllllt Mlrt pitl7onfi Ofllentltta nrn\nvided, of course, that the amount\nso allotted shall not exceed what\nthe county itself would be enti\ntled to. We think this should\nbe a part of the law for the ben\nelit of some progressive persons\nwho may happen to live in coun\nties that will not vote bonds to\nbuild pikes.\nThe business outlook for Olay\nCity and Powell county for the\nNew Year is as bright as usual\nand possibly a little brighter.\nThe county is gradually working\nout of debt and getting ready to\nbuild some of those good roads,\nthat so many of our best citizens\nhave been going to the Bluegrass\nto get. Getting money should\nnot be foremost in our eyes. A\nfit habitation for man and his\nchildren are far more to be de\nsired. Let us strive to that end,\natid first let us build good roads\nto travel the route over.\ns\nI WW be.\nr. QPQQT\nHowever strange it may seem,\nthere is a sentiment among some\nPowell county good citizens a\ngainst good roads, and we have\nlost four good paying subscribers\nin the county on account of our\npersistent advocacy of good roads.\nThey have irgued with us that\ngood roads will not make their\nlaud grow a single ear of corn\nmore, but it will increase the\nmarket value of their laud which\nwill make their taxes higher, and\nfor this reason, they oppose good\nroads. They think taxes are now\nhigh enough. p\nWhile far from beingwhat we\nwould have it, Christmas was\nmore soberly spent than usual,\nthough to he sure there wns much\nliquor consumed by those accus\ntomed to its use. It was, how\never, apparently, a decided im\nprovement over former years\nwith the open saloon.\nSometimes when a futher gives\nhis children noise making toys it\nis a sign that he has n grudge u\ngairt the neighbors.\n''It is more blessed to give than\nto receive\" is acceptable with\nmost men if it is advice that is\nbeing dealt out.\nTHE OHIO FARMER\nrOn the past quarter of a century, thero hn li-rn one\nrami Paper that has stood out iiom It fellow like a\nray of sunshine through n murky sky; by lti straight\nforward and fearless attltudo on every bin question nlleet\nlng the public In general anil the farmer In particular; by\nIts unchanging policy of accepting for implication, only the\nniivcrtlslriK or established and reputable concerns; by Its\nunfaltering aJvocacy of everything that has contributed\nto the betterment of the farmer. Ins iamlly and farm. It\nlias emblazoned Its name at the very forefront of Tho\nAmerican Tarm I'rcss Till', OHIO t'XlWMl.\nl'rom 20 to 48 pases every week. Mngnz'nc section de\nToted to high-class fiction, truvrl and kclcucc sketches,\npoetry, article for boys nnd girls. He.\nllEGULAU PIUCE, 50 CLXTS A YEAH.\nTODAY'S irACAZINF.\nTODAY'S MAGAZINE is n monthly nnd contains from\n32 to 41 pages, 11 Inches uM\", lii Iru-iies Ion,;. It In a\nlarge, complete vromnn's niwuli'.C, full of grnrnd Informa\ntion of Interest, livery Issue contains attractive articles\non timely subjects wrlttrii by tht fotemott men and\nwomen of the clay. Its iaes nrc fi 11 of the. rholrest kind\nof literature relating to hLlory, travel, science. Invention,\nart, drama, education, religion, imtsl,-, l'u-lilom, needle\nwork, hairdresslng, horio ilrrsmnUln, health, liyslcue,\ncooking, short stories and s